## 4. Mock FileSystem

### Using `FileSystem.makeNoop` (RECOMMENDED)

`@effect/platform/FileSystem` exports `makeNoop` at line 358 of the `.d.ts`:

```typescript
export declare const makeNoop: (fileSystem: Partial<FileSystem>) => FileSystem;
```

This is the **simplest** approach: provide only the methods your test needs. Unused methods return sensible defaults (no-op).

### Minimum mock methods required

| Method            | SoulSpecLoader | ActiveSoulPersistence | Used in                                                       |
| ----------------- | -------------- | --------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `exists`          | ✅             | ✅                    | Loader: `resolveSoulPath`, `getAllSouls`; Persistence: `load` |
| `readFileString`  | ✅             | ✅                    | Loader: `readJsonFile`, `readTextFile`; Persistence: `load`   |
| `readDirectory`   | ✅             | ❌                    | Loader: `getAllSouls`                                         |
| `writeFileString` | ❌             | ✅                    | Persistence: `save`                                           |
| `makeDirectory`   | ❌             | ✅                    | Persistence: `save` (mkdir parent dir)                        |
| `remove`          | ❌             | ✅                    | Persistence: `clear`                                          |

### Mock implementation (complete)

```typescript
import { Effect } from "effect";
import { FileSystem } from "@effect/platform/FileSystem";

// Map of path→content for in-memory file system
type MemoryFs = Map<string, string>;

function createTestFs(files: MemoryFs, dirs: string[]): FileSystem.FileSystem {
  return FileSystem.makeNoop({
    exists: (path: string) => Effect.succeed(files.has(path) || dirs.includes(path)),
    readFileString: (path: string) => {
      const content = files.get(path);
      if (content !== undefined) return Effect.succeed(content);
      return Effect.fail(new Error(`ENOENT: ${path}`));
    },
    readDirectory: (path: string) => {
      if (dirs.includes(path)) {
        // Return directory names that have children in our file map
        const entries = new Set<string>();
        for (const filePath of files.keys()) {
          if (filePath.startsWith(path + "/")) {
            const rest = filePath.slice(path.length + 1);
            const dirName = rest.split("/")[0];
            entries.add(dirName);
          }
        }
        return Effect.succeed(Array.from(entries));
      }
      return Effect.fail(new Error(`ENOENT: ${path}`));
    },
    writeFileString: (_path: string, _data: string) => Effect.void,
    makeDirectory: (_path: string, _options?: any) => Effect.void,
    remove: (_path: string, _options?: any) => Effect.void,
  });
}
```

### Path resolution for `expandHome`

Note that `expandHome` is a **sync** function (not Effect). It reads `process.env.HOME` directly. In tests it will use the actual user's home directory. For exact path matching, either:

1. Set `process.env.HOME` before tests and restore after
2. Accept that expanded paths will match expanded paths in the loader

The test FS should accept paths in their **expanded** form (since `expandHome` is called before FileSystem calls).

